<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" color="#663366" size=2> <b>Not all who wander are lost. - J.R.R. Tolkien </b></font><br></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/unosferum.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nosferum</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_ball.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Thane</span><br>  Posts: 386<br> <font color=#330000>(7/29/01 12:10:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ftheclanmacleargeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1123.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.premiernet.net/~chandler/images/baldnos.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: So dumb, it actually baffles me.</span><hr size=1> ---&quot;Lock ups&quot; is probably the most daunting of all computer problems. To be honest, every little thing in your computer could, potentially, cause the computer to lock up. More specifically, though, if it's not one device, it's the way that one device interacts with another.<br>
<br>
---If your friend is using Win9x, they can go to My Computer &gt; Control Panel &gt; Sytem. In the new window, there's a tab called Device Manager that they should click on. If ANY of the icons there, or those within the subsections) show an exclaimatino point as part of the icon there is a potential conflict that COULD be causing the lock ups. Conversely, If &quot;Computer&quot; is selected once at the top of the list, have them select the Properties button down below. It should open a new window with a list of devices in your computer, each with their own number. If two items are using the same number, that could POTENTIALLY cause a problem, but not necessarily. You'd ned a technician, first-hand, decide that.<br>
<br>
---Way back in the day, I played Fallout on this computer. The game (and only that game-- no others) would lock up my entire computer. Considering it was a new game at the time, I presumed it was the game and patiently waited for a Patch from their website. No go. Eventually, I replaced my Network Card and the problems went away, despite the fact that my NIC worked fine otherwise and the fact that this game never used that card. <p><IMG SRC="http://www.premiernet.net/~chandler/images/newmaclogo3.gif"></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#deddbf><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/utormodmaclear.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Tormod MacLear</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Chief</span><br>  Posts: 421<br> <font color=#330000>(7/29/01 4:35:33 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ftheclanmacleargeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1123.topic&index=6>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.clanmaclear.com/images/tormod.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: So dumb, it actually baffles me.</span><hr size=1> After reading this you all may conclude that I am demented, but over the years since I left the belly of the beast, I have found great riches and fortune in being so. My youngest son, Jon (Daran the Flea) made the observation, &quot;Men are from Mars and women are from Venus, but Dad is from Pluto.&quot;<br>
<br>
You gentlemen are wizards, mages, magicians. Is as if the legends have come to life. You may think of what you do in technical terms, but what are the many programs you use but spells (you even have to spell each word, literally)? You have the magic words to inscribe that are necessary to bring the various spells (programs) together with the required reagents (hardware) to make mystic things happen. Fortunately for the rest of us, you have the capability to make some of the spells fairly persistant (like this message board) and are good enough to let us know the mystic words of passing that allow us to &quot;come&quot; to this board in the nether realms where physical beings may not venture to pass etheral messages to one another instantly without need for physical contact.<br>
<br>
If you will allow your viewpoint to change just a bit you will recognize that you are in indeed workers of true magic. You simply have a problem with the tricksters that have not studied the arcane books yet attempt to use either real or false reagents and seek your mystic knowledge without the labor and sacrifice necessary.<br>
<br>
There are even evil mages about, the crackers who would destroy the spells you have woven so carefully and even the reagents themselves. Against them you place counter spells and counter spell reagents throughout your etheral realm.<br>
<br>
This is something just beginning, in the years to come those like you will have power to topple even those who think they govern.<br>
<br>
I recently had the opportunity to meet a warrior mage. Tormod the Younger was up until recently employed by the Air Intelligence Agency. One of his friends there is an officer (knight) who's job was to attack friendly computer systems both from without and within. We set up a firewall and the most sophisticated protection we could think of and he was through it in about thirty seconds. <br>
<br>
He told us that the next war would at least start with informations systems warfare utilizing people like him on both sides in the attempt to destroy the command, control, and intelligence systems of the other. He suggsted that the day might come when an entire war could be fought in cyberspace with the loser unable to wag war in the physical world and forced to surrender without a shot fired.<br>
<br>
He explained that he had the capability to shut down power grids, stop all air traffic, effectively prevent a government from communicating with itself or its people, and shut down the food distribution system for that too is run by computer.<br>
<br>
You good folks are are on the fringes of something as amazing and world changing as the discovery of metal forging. Let us hope that you are both very very good and very very trustworthy, for your power may be beyond our imagination. <p>For Halas! For MacLear!<BR>
Spectamur Agendo!<BR>
<BR>
Tormod MacLear, Chief</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#cccb9b><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub5.ezboard.com/btheclanmaclear.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=jeffryn>Jeffryn</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Kin</span><br>  Posts: 14<br> <font color=#330000>(7/30/01 10:34:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub5.ezboard.com/ftheclanmacleargeneral.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1123.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: So dumb, it actually baffles me.</span><hr size=1> Aye, I have a fresh one from the war fields, and t'bad that Tabot missed it, 'tis a good chuckle.<br>
<br>
T'is one thing with a user remarks on something that makes us shake our heads in disbelief and allow ourselves to gather in the glow of the elitism of our knowledge...<br>
<br>
...but 'tis altogether another when the sys.admins from above remark on something that makes your jaw drop and ye have to wonder WITFH he is smoking in the wee hours. <br>
<br>
Case in point....  We got a Trouble Ticket from a state-wide admin complaining that a cable modem user appears to be abusing a cgi script and we should check it out. The &quot;script&quot; in this case is srch.dll, from icq.com...which if you have ever done a user search on the webpage you would see it being used to get user details. The user was *simply* doing a lot of searches on that website.  So, now am I to contact this customer and say &quot;Sorry, bucko, you can't look for new friends!&quot;<br>
<br>
Bah.<br>
<br>
